<p>
  Here are some changes we are going to make:
</p>
<ul>
  <li>
    In all of the kinematic equations, the variable \( \Delta x \)
    for displacement has been displaced with \( \Delta y \).
    This is beacuse \( y \) is used as a variable when motion is vertical.
  </li>
  <li>
    Because when an object is falling, its vertical displacement is downward,
    we are going to use a <emph>negative</emph> value for \( \Delta y \).
  </li>
  <li>
    An object is accelerating at a rate of 9.8 m/s<sup>2</sup> downward.
  </li>
  <li>
    Also, whenever velocity isn't zero, it will be neagtive (until we get to problems with objects thrown upward).
  </li>
</ul>

